The US-China tech war
Originating from New York — — the worst diplomatic decision made by the previous generation (and even earlier generations) of Americans is the "war of choice" launched in 2003 against Iraq, which claimed to aim at eliminating — — in reality, non-existent — — weapons of mass destruction.
The necessity to understand the flawed logic behind this disastrous decision has become more pressing than ever, as the same logic is being used to justify similar US misleading policies today.
The decision to invade Iraq was made under the flawed logic of then-US Vice President Richard Cheney, who claimed that the risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists was very small (e.g., 1%) and that we should act as if this were to happen.
However, this reasoning approach almost always leads to incorrect decisions.
However, the US and some of its allies are currently using Cheneyism to attack Chinese technology.
According to the US government, since we cannot be sure that Chinese technology is safe, we should approach it with the understanding that it is certainly harmful and impose a ban on it.
A correct decision would apply probability estimates to each alternative measure.
A generation ago, US policymakers should have considered not only the (claimed) 1% risk of weapons of mass destruction falling into the hands of terrorists, but also the 99% risk of launching a war based on multiple flawed assumptions.
By simply emphasizing that 1% risk, Cheney (and many others) diverted public attention and made people overlook the fact that the Iraq War lacked legitimacy and severely destabilized the stability of the Middle East and global politics.
But the problem with Cheneyism is not just that it acts on tiny risks without considering extremely high potential costs, but that politicians will always whip up fear for some unknown purpose.
This is what American leaders are doing again: stirring up panic about Chinese tech companies by pointing out and exaggerating some tiny risks.
The most relevant (though not the only) case is the US government's attack on the Chinese tech company Huawei.
The US is gradually closing down the company's domestic market and trying to strangle its global business.
Like Iraq, the US may ultimately cause an unwarranted geopolitical disaster.
I have worked in developing countries and have been following Huawei's technological progress, because I believe that 5G and other digital technologies can provide a huge driving force for achieving the United Nations' Sustainable Development Goals, such as eradicating poverty.
I have had similar interactions with other telecommunications companies and have encouraged the industry to take more action towards achieving the Sustainable Development Goals.
I wrote a short foreword (unpaid) for a report by Huawei on this topic, which was criticized by those who are hostile to China, so I asked industry leaders and government officials if there was any evidence that Huawei had engaged in any unusual behavior, and repeatedly received the answer that Huawei's actions were no different from those of other trustworthy industry leaders.
Despite this, the US government still believes that Huawei's 5G devices may harm global security.
US officials claim that the "backdoors" in Huawei software or hardware could allow the Chinese government to monitor people globally.
They point out that China's laws require Chinese companies to cooperate with the government for national security reasons.
But the facts are now clear.
Huawei's 5G devices are affordable, high-quality, and currently lead many competitors, and have already begun to be promoted.
Its high-performance capabilities come from massive investments in research over the years, economies of scale, and its presence in the Chinese digital market.
Given the importance of this technology for its sustainable development, it would be foolish for low-income economies around the world to refuse to adopt 5G anytime soon.
However, despite the lack of evidence for the existence of backdoors, the US is still lobbying the world to stay away from Huawei.
The US claim is universal.
As a US Federal Communications Commissioner said: "Countries that own 5G will have related innovations and set standards for the rest of the world, and that country is unlikely to be the US at this point."
Other countries – especially the UK – have not found any backdoors in Huawei's software or hardware yet.
Even if backdoors are discovered in the future, they can almost certainly be closed at that time.
The debate over Huawei is also intense in Germany, as the US government has threatened to cut intelligence cooperation unless authorities block Huawei's 5G technology.
Perhaps under pressure from the US, the head of the German intelligence agency recently made a statement similar to Cheneyism: "The infrastructure is not a field suitable for a group that cannot be fully trusted to be involved in."
However, he did not provide any concrete evidence of wrongdoing.
In contrast, Chancellor Merkel is reportedly fighting behind the scenes to keep the market open to Huawei.
The irony is that the US complaints actually partly reflect the US own domestic and foreign surveillance activities — although this is no longer news.
Chinese equipment may make it harder for the US government to implement secret surveillance.
However, any government's unlawful surveillance activities should stop.
Independent oversight by the UN to reduce such activities should become part of the global telecommunications system.
In short, we should choose diplomacy and institutional guarantees over a technology war.
The threatening impact of the US demand to ban Huawei is not limited to the early adoption of 5G networks, but also poses a huge risk to rule-based trading systems.
Now the US is no longer the uncontested global technological leader, and US President Trump and his advisors do not want to compete in a rule-based system.
Their goal is to curb China's technological rise.
They are also trying to undermine the World Trade Organization by disabling its dispute settlement mechanism, which reflects their pattern of disregard for global rules.
If the Trump administration succeeds in "dividing the world into different technological camps," the risk of conflict will increase exponentially in the future.
After World War II, the US promoted open trade, not only to increase global efficiency and expand the US technology market, but also to reverse the collapse of international trade in the 1930s.
While one of the reasons for the collapse is the protectionist tariffs imposed by the US under the Smoot-Hawley Tariff Act of 1930, which exacerbated the Great Depression and ultimately led to the rise of Hitler and the outbreak of World War II.
As in other fields, inspiring fear and acting on it – rather than following evidence – is a path to destruction in international affairs.
Let us stick to reason, evidence, and rules – the safest course of action.
Let us establish independent monitoring agencies to reduce the threat of any country using global networks to surveil other countries or launch cyber warfare.
In this way, the world can quickly leverage breakthrough digital technologies to achieve global well-being.
